ected by francophone medieval poets and compilers keen to devise their own literary history.Stolen Song makes a major contribution to medieval studies both by exposing this act of cultural appropriation as the origin of the French canon and by elaborating a new approach to questions of political and cultural identity. Eliza Zingesser shows that these questions, usually addressed on the level of narrative and theme, can also be fruitfully approached through formal, linguistic, and manuscript-oriented tools.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aFrench literatureyTo 1500xHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature, MedievalxProvençal influences. 0aLiterature, MedievalxProvençal influences. 0aPoetry, MedievalxHistory and criticism. 0aProvençal poetryxHistory and criticism. 0aProvençal poetryxHistory and criticism. 0aQuotations in literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aTroubadour songsxInfluence. 0aTroubadours. 4aFrance. 4aMedieval & Renaissance Studies. 4aMusical Arts & Ethnomusicology. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aTroubadours, medieval song, Richard de Fournival, Jean Renart, Gerbert de Montreuil.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069046008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020 Englishz978311070473008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020z9783110704525oZDB-23-DEG40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501747649zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501747649423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9